1 STATE OF OKLAHOMA
2 1st Session of the 60th Legislature (2025)
4
5
6 AS INTRODUCED
7 An Act relating to agriculture; enacting the Oklahoma
Right to Garden Act of 2025; defining terms;
8 providing the right to grow vegetables in a vegetable
garden for personal consumption; providing that a
9 municipality, city, or town may enact certain
content-neutral ordinances regulating vegetable
10 gardens; providing for codification; and providing an
effective date.
11
12
13 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
14 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
15 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3031 of Title 2, unless there is
16 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
17 This act shall be known and may be cited as the "Oklahoma Right
18 to Garden Act of 2025".
19 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
20 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3032 of Title 2, unless there is
21 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
22 As used in this act:
23 1. "Residential property" means real property on which there is
24 a dwelling unit with accommodations for four or fewer separate
Req. No. 10419 Page 1
1 hous eholds and is further limited to the primary residence of a
2 person; and
3 2. "Vegetable garden" means a piece of property wholly located
4 within a person's residential property that is used to grow produce,
5 flowers, herbs, fungi, or grains for one's own consumption and
6 enjoyment and not for resale or distribution.
7 SECTION 3. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
8 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3033 of Title 2, unless there is
9 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
10 A. It shall be the right of citizens of the State of Oklahoma
11 to engage in growing their own vegetables in a vegetable garden on
12 their personal property for personal consumption, subject to
13 restrictions rationally related to a governmental purpose.
14 B. Notwithstanding, this section shall not prohibit any
15 municipality, city, or town from enacting content-neutral ordinances
16 or regulations that address the following:
17 1. Limiting the size and proximity of gardens to roadways,
18 structures, or other locations that impact health and safety; or
19 2. The enforcement of constitutional and lawful ordinances
20 adopted by municipalities that are in conformity with general powers
21 of municipal governments within this state that are of a general
22 nature that do not specifically ban gardening, including, but not
23 limited to, regulations and ordinances relating to water usage
24
Req. No. 10419 Page 2
1 duri ng drought conditions, fertilizer use, or control of invasive
2 species.
3 SECTION 4. This act shall become effective November 1, 2025.
